MY TASKS OF PROJECT REQUIREMENT ANALYSIS


Task1.1:DATA GATHERING. 
. Interviews (Management & Key Staff)
Findings:
•	Management feels the current CRM lacks integration with the POS system, leading to duplicate entries.
•	Sales managers report difficulty tracking leads and follow-ups, resulting in lost opportunities.
•	Marketing team struggles to segment customers for targeted campaigns.
•	Customer service notes delays in retrieving purchase history during support calls.
2. Employee Questionnaire (Sales, Marketing, Support Staff)
Responses (summarized):
•	Ease of Use: 65% say the system is “complicated” and requires too many manual steps.
•	Functionality: Sales staff want automated reminders for follow-ups; marketing wants campaign analytics; support wants faster search.
•	Integration: 70% report they use spreadsheets outside the CRM to fill gaps.
•	Suggestions: Better dashboards, mobile access, and integration with e-commerce.
3. Customer Feedback Form
Insights:
•	Customers feel promotions are “generic” and not tailored to their shopping history.
•	40% report repeating information when contacting support (system doesn’t recognize them).
•	Many want loyalty rewards tracked digitally instead of paper receipts.
•	Overall satisfaction score: 6.5/10.
4. Observation Checklist
Observed Issues:
•	Staff take 2–3 minutes to retrieve customer records.
•	Manual entry of sales data is common.
•	Duplicate customer profiles exist.
•	Workarounds: staff export data to Excel for reporting.
5. Documentation Checklist
Collected Artifacts:
•	Current CRM user manual (outdated, last updated 3 years ago).
•	Monthly sales reports (inconsistent formatting).
•	Customer service logs (not linked to CRM).
•	Integration notes with POS (partial, not fully implemented).
 Analysis
•	Key Inefficiencies: Lack of integration, slow data retrieval, poor analytics, duplicate records.
•	Impact: Lost sales opportunities, generic customer engagement, reduced satisfaction.
•	Opportunities: Automation, better segmentation, loyalty program integration, mobile-friendly CRM.
 Next Steps for Client Meeting
When presenting to the client:
1.	Show pain points with evidence (quotes, stats, observations).
2.	Propose solutions:
o	Unified CRM integrated with POS & e-commerce.
o	Automated lead tracking and reminders.
o	Customer segmentation for personalized marketing.
o	Loyalty program digitization.
3.	Prioritize requirements into must-have vs nice-to-have.
4.	Confirm alignment with client expectations before moving to design.






TASK1.2:INTERPRITATION OF DATA.
________________________________________
1. Interpreting Typical User Data (What to Look For)
a) User Preferences
From surveys, clicks, and enrollments:
•	High demand for short, structured courses → users prefer modular learning (microlearning) 
•	Popular categories (e.g., coding, business, exam prep) → prioritize these first 
•	Device usage (mobile vs desktop) 
o	If most users are mobile → mobile-first design is critical 
Interpretation:
Users want flexible, accessible, and practical learning content
________________________________________
b) Engagement Patterns
From analytics (time spent, drop-off rates, session duration):
•	High drop-off in long videos → content is too lengthy or not engaging 
•	High engagement in quizzes/tutorials → interactive content works better 
•	Frequent logins but low completion → motivation or tracking issues 
Interpretation:
Users engage more with:
•	Interactive content 
•	Short lessons 
•	Clear progress tracking 
________________________________________
c) User Feedback (Reviews / Comments)
From surveys, forums, ratings:
Common complaints:
•	“Courses are too long” 
•	“No clear progress tracking” 
•	“Hard to navigate” 
•	“Lack of community support” 
Positive feedback:
•	“Interactive exercises are helpful” 
•	“Personal dashboards are useful” 
Interpretation:
Users value:
•	Simplicity 
•	Feedback systems 
•	Community interaction 
________________________________________
2. Data Visualization Insights (What Trends Reveal)
Using charts like:
•	Bar charts → popular courses 
•	Line graphs → engagement over time 
•	Heatmaps → user clicks/navigation 
You typically uncover:
•	Peak usage times → schedule content releases or notifications 
•	Most clicked features → highlight them on homepage 
•	Navigation bottlenecks → redesign UI/UX 
________________________________________
3. Key Features Identified (Based on Data)
From the interpretation above, the system should include:
Core Features (High Priority)
•	Course catalog with filters (category, difficulty, duration) 
•	Interactive tutorials (quizzes, coding exercises) 
•	Personalized dashboard: 
o	Progress tracking 
o	Recommendations 
•	Mobile-friendly UI 
Engagement Features
•	Gamification (badges, streaks) 
•	Notifications/reminders 
•	Short lesson formats 
Community Features
•	Discussion forums 
•	Peer interaction 
•	Instructor Q&A 
________________________________________
4. Functional Requirements
•	Users can: 
o	Register/login 
o	Enroll in courses 
o	Track progress 
o	Participate in forums 
•	Admin can: 
o	Upload/manage courses 
o	Monitor user activity 
•	System: 
o	Recommends courses based on behavior 
o	Tracks completion rates 
________________________________________
5. Non-Functional Requirements
•	Fast loading speed (important for mobile users) 
•	Scalable system (many users) 
•	Secure authentication 
•	User-friendly interface 
________________________________________
6. Final Insight (What the Data Tells You)
If we summarize all interpreted trends:
The platform must prioritize personalization, interactivity, and simplicity over just content quantity.
